Raymond James Financial | Services and Products | Raymond James Trust N.A. | Consider Charitable Giving in 2012




















OUR COMPANY



PERSONAL INVESTING
INSTITUTIONAL & CORPORATE
ADVISOR OPPORTUNITIES


ACCOUNT LOGIN







Consider charitable giving in 2012
Donate this year and reduce your overall tax burden
A charitable donation can provide a feeling of personal satisfaction. It may also result in a more tangible return for you in the form of desirable tax benefits. And given the pending tax changes that are expected to impact charitable contributions in 2013, now may be the time to give to your favorite charity before the end of 2012.
Most of the time, donations of cash, real estate or other assets to qualified charities count as an itemized deduction for that tax year. The deductibility of charitable gifts is based on several factors, including the donor’s income, the nature of the donation and the charity receiving the donation.
Here’s what to expect in terms of charitable giving changes from 2012 to 2013:

There are proposed changes to limit the total value of itemized deductions to no more than 28% of adjusted gross income for taxpayers in the proposed 36% and 39.6% brackets. Under this scenario, a charitable donation would provide significantly reduced tax savings in 2013 versus 2012. In simple terms, if you were to make a $10,000 donation to a charity of choice, you could only claim a $2,800 deduction on your taxes if you waited until 2013 to make the donation versus a $3,960 deduction (for the highest tax bracket) if the donation is made by December 31, 2012.
The level of allowed itemized deductions, including charitable donations, for higher-income taxpayers (sometimes called the 3% haircut) is also slated to return in 2013. Basically, taxpayers with adjusted gross incomes over the applicable threshold (a proposed $261,450 for couples in 2013) would lose deductions equal to 3% of the excess up to a maximum of 80%. There is also a proposal to limit all itemized deductions to a fixed dollar maximum.

Charitable giving in 2012 is a viable strategy to possibly minimize your overall tax burden. In addition to donating assets tax-free, a 2012 charitable donation strategy could also help put your taxable estate into a lower tax bracket by removing assets from the estate. There are no limits on the amount that you can pass to a charity, but there may be an optimum donation amount to consider, depending on your overall tax situation, the charity of choice and your family values.
It’s important to consider other ways to position charitable giving for maximum tax advantages, such as using charitable contributions to offset a conversion of a traditional IRA (or other qualified retirement assets) to a Roth IRA in 2012.
When determining the right kind of charitable giving strategy, your Raymond James financial advisor can help you. Your advisor will also work with your CPA or tax professional to coordinate the most appropriate tax strategies for your situation. Remember, what is most critical is establishing your personal goals for both the short and long term. Tax strategies can be used to help you achieve these goals and should be utilized within the context of your overall financial picture.




